With respect to the condition of the common people, there are some slight yet clear indicationS, that they were not stinted in their means. Clean sheets were reason- ably expected in the cottage of the churl; and the ale-house keeper and the vintner invited the guest in the upland towns.

All the lands of Roger de Mortimer in the County of Norfolk, are seized into the King's hands because he had tourneyed without the King's licence. But Mortimer finds pledges· that, before the feast of St. Hilary,he will make his peace, or compound with the King. His pledges are Roget Earl Bigod‚ Galfridus de Say, and William de Warenna3 and the Sheriff is thereupon commanded to let him have his lands again.
